"{\n  \"missions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"M08\",\n      \"title\": \"Breathing the Drowned Library\",\n      \"quest_giver\": {\"name\": \"Jana Fell\", \"affiliation\": \"Inkroot Archivists\"},\n      \"description\": \"The Sunken Archive of Thren slept under blackwater like a cathedral that had learned to breathe, inhaling and exhaling silt-sweet currents through ruptured arches and kelp-draped halls. Marble stacks leaned with algae shawls, their spine-etchings furred with moss and the fine grit of centuries, while stone librarians paced with cold lanterns cupped in hands that remembered flame without warmth. Bottled wind still hissed from a cracked reliquary somewhere in the western vault, a glass-thin whistle threading the water and tugging at boats as if the lake itself were lonely for voices, or for law. Jana Fell’s request came on parchment tough as fish-skin and sealed in honeyed amber: rescue hinge-craft treatises and flood-law precedent from the western stacks, copy lost diagrams the Tidewrights claimed by inheritance, and make sure the truth came up cleaner than the river’s own teeth. Orren Halv, Syndic of sluices and law by torque, sent a rasping addendum: diagrams of the western hinge-pivot or nothing, and if the constructs glowered, to answer with chord and precedent. Neris Quay stood on the weed-slick shore with ash-mask ready and bowcord waxed, Copper-thread luck glinting in tar-black braid, and the Mirrorglass signal mirror warm against the palm like a kept secret. The water pressed against the mask like an old grudge, and the city’s future pressed like a hand between the shoulder blades, urging a descent that felt too much like a vow. Lamps burned on the far banks in colors that meant commerce, caution, and compromise; their reflections shivered into threads that Neris imagined stitching into a safety net for this dive and all the dives to come. When the first kick took Neris under, the river-slick world steadied, and the drowned library opened its ribs to a visitor who had remembered to breathe.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Negotiate passage with a stone librarian by offering a correctly knotted visitor cord and a catalog of intended shelves.\",\n        \"Retrieve waterproof vellum etched with breathing runes and a labradorite tile that glows when truth is spoken.\",\n        \"Close the rift where bottled wind still hisses by weighting it with basalt and singing a hinge-song phrase.\",\n        \"Copy hinge diagrams without triggering construct jealousy or page-ward curses.\",\n        \"Deliver a set of flood-law precedents to the Archivists and a redacted diagram to the Syndicate.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Stone Librarian\", \"lines\": \"Breath is allowed if declared, and you will declare it as one declares a tool before opening a case: clearly, calmly, and without embellishment. Hands will be permitted if gloved, for oil is a vandal we have learned to recognize even in the dark, and we do not forgive easily when pages remember a touch that hurt them. Intention will be cataloged and returned in the same condition in which it was provided, or penalties will accrue according to the drowned index that we recite without air and without haste. You will not elevate your voice above the level of our lantern’s echo, for sound is a current here and every current is measured, weighed, and given back to the shelves that birthed it. Declare your name and your bindings, and we will weigh your passage as we weigh storms in jars and maps in the bones of fish. If what you seek is law, you will wear a cord whose knot speaks of witness; if what you seek is craft, you will knot for function and show us you know the difference.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Jana Fell\", \"lines\": \"I have argued with judges and ledgers and once with my own conscience, and none are as stubborn as a library that has tasted its own mortality and decided it will not be fooled again. We must bring up what will keep our city from repeating Thren’s last page, and we must do it with gloves on our souls as well as our hands. Sing to the wind if it will listen, because even a bottled gale has ears for a right chord, and the hinges of Avarinth have always answered to music that respects the weight of water. If it will not listen, gag it with stone and law, for both were made to stop a thing that believes itself unstoppable, and both have stopped me in my youth when I ran too hot. You are to copy what must be copied and keep your shadow from touching what would follow you home; I will tie your intent to a witness-knot and you will feel it at your wrist like a pulse. When you return, we will divide truth from vanity and oath from rumor, and the city will have one less darkness in a place where the lamps cannot go.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Orren Halv\", \"lines\": \"I do not beg favors from statues, but I will give thanks to any rock that lets me read, because rock remembers the shape of pressure better than any clerk remembers the shape of a river’s mind. Fetch me the diagram for the western hinge-pivot, and give Jana her law, for I would rather be argued with by a clean page than by a flood that thinks it knows what it wants. If the constructs hiss at you, hiss back in proper chord, and they will either understand or prove themselves furniture, and I know how to move furniture. If they bite, bite harder with precedent, because teeth chip on statute when statute has been tempered in a calamity’s fire. Bring me a redacted copy that hides our safety tolerances from fools and saboteurs, and keep the breathing vellum from any who think reading it in a mirror makes them engineers. If you must choose between a perfect diagram and a living city, favor the city, and I will take my scolding from scholars with my hat off and my lamp lit.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Neris Quay\", \"lines\": \"My knot is true and my cord is clean, and the witness loop lies on the inside of my wrist where I can feel it tighten if I lie to myself. I will take what I declare and leave no finger marks you can smell, and if I fail that, I will leave my name tied to the fault so it can be found and scolded by anyone with a better memory. If the wind tries to walk me where it wants, I will sing it into a chair and ask it to listen, because even angry weather understands a firm voice offered with respect. The pages will hear my breath but not my hunger, and if my shadow grows sharp, I will fold it like a sail and knot it to the floor until my work is done. I am riverborn and taught by roofs and ropes, and I have balanced worse ledgers than this one when the lamps burned red and the city pretended not to see. If Thren’s drowned law wants me to pay a tithe of time, I will pay it in patience and clean copies, and I will not take more than we agreed even if the shelves whisper my name like a familiar sin.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Ink Eel Whisper\", \"lines\": \"Warm skin warm skin warm skin, the law is meat if we close our eyes and float inside the dark that tastes like iron and old coins. Bleed a little and we will tell you the secret names of the hinges, and we will wind them around your knuckles like ribbons that bite when you pull too hard. Don’t bleed and we will tell the water you are rude, and the water will tuck you into a pocket behind a sigh and forget where it put you for a hundred bell-chimes. We learned to read by drinking spills and mistakes, and we love mistakes best because they hum when you put your ear to them. Stay still and we will comb your hair with our small teeth and leave you smooth as a page that has been forgiven by the sun.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Present the perfect visitor cord and a full shelf catalog\", \"text\": \"Neris double-checks the visitor cord, fingers counting the witness loops and the catalog knot where shelf numbers are tucked like seeds. The cord is offered palm-up, n