nd names the danger of delay, painting the bottled wind as a liability that will cost the Archive more pages if not silenced. There is respect in the words but not much softness, just the crisp logic of men and women who close teeth of basalt against a tide that wants to swallow their neighbors. The final sentence offers a reciprocal favor in the city above, and the lantern flashes in the cadence of power rather than petition.\", \"outcome\": \"The stone librarian steps aside but its lantern narrows to a slit of measured disapproval, and a second construct begins to pace two aisles over like a magistrate who expects to be needed. The air-pressure tides start to pulse faster, as if the Archive itself holds its breath against the tone, and the ink eels gather with a whispering curiosity that thrums in the ribs. Copying is still possible, but page-wards stiffen and a mirrored panel turns its face away so that reflections cannot sneak extra glances. When the hinge-song is needed later, the room remembers the command and resists the lullaby, so the bottled wind bites once before it can be caged. The work is finished on time, but a rumor travels upward in the bubbles that a Syndicate seal leaned too hard on a sacred place, and Jana’s trust needs mending with a clean citation and an apology tied in public cord.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Close the bottled wind with song and measured stone\", \"text\": \"Neris chooses the hinge-phrase taught by rain and rope, testing the pitch against the gantry-bones of memory until a resonance wakes in the mask itself. Basalt weights are set like quiet commas around the rift, each placed on a pulse rather than a point the eye would pick first. The song begins low and patient and then rises through the tones that tides answer, not as command but as pact sworn in breath and labor. The bottled wind seethes in its cracked prison and then curls like a scolded animal, finding that the song names its shape more gently than glass 